{"id":"1906.07737","submitter":"Jonathan Stern","authors":"Jonathan Stern, Drummond Fielding, Claude-Andr\\'e Faucher-Gigu\\`ere\n  and Eliot Quataert","title":"Cooling flow solutions for the circumgalactic medium","comments":"26 pages, 18 figures. Accepted to MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stz1859","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.GA astro-ph.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In several models of galaxy formation feedback occurs in cycles or mainly at\nhigh redshift. At times and in regions where feedback heating is ineffective,\nhot gas in the galaxy halo is expected to form a cooling flow, where the gas\nadvects inward on a cooling timescale. Cooling flow solutions can thus be used\nas a benchmark for observations and simulations to constrain the timing and\nextent of feedback heating. Using analytic calculations and idealized 3D\nhydrodynamic simulations, we show that for a given halo mass and cooling\nfunction, steady-state cooling flows form a single-parameter family of\nsolutions, while initially hydrostatic gaseous halos converge on one of these\nsolutions within a cooling time. The solution is thus fully determined once\neither the mass inflow rate $\\dot{M}$ or the total halo gas mass are known. In\nthe Milky Way (MW) halo, a cooling flow with $\\dot{M}$ equal to the star\nformation rate predicts a ratio of the cooling time to the free-fall time of\n~10, similar to some feedback-regulated models. This solution also correctly\npredicts observed OVII and OVIII absorption columns, and the gas density\nprofile implied by OVII and OVIII emission. These results suggest ongoing\nheating by feedback may be negligible in the inner MW halo. Extending similar\nsolutions out to the cooling radius however underpredicts observed OVI columns\naround the MW and around other low-redshift star-forming galaxies. This can be\nreconciled with the successes of the cooling flow model with either a mechanism\n